Multithreading

⭐⭐⭐ MOST MOST IMPORTANT

1️⃣ What is a Thread in Java?
Answer (Interview-Winning):

A thread is a lightweight unit of execution within a process. Java supports multithreading to perform multiple tasks concurrently within a single program, 
improving CPU utilization and responsiveness.

Example:
For example, in a web application, one thread handles a user request while another thread processes database operations.

Contrast line:
A process has its own memory, but threads share the same memory.

2️⃣ How do you create a thread in Java?
Answer:

There are two ways:
a. Extending Thread class

Creating Thread using Thread class
class MyThread extends Thread {

    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread is running using Thread class");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyThread t1 = new MyThread();
        t1.start();   // starts a new thread
    }
}

What to say in interview (1 line):
“Here I extend the Thread class and override the run method. Calling start() creates a new thread and internally invokes run().”

b. Implementing Runnable interface

Creating Thread using Runnable interface (PREFERRED)

class MyRunnable implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread is running using Runnable interface");
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Thread t1 = new Thread(new MyRunnable());
        t1.start();   // starts a new thread
    }
}

What to say in interview (1 line):
“Runnable is preferred because it allows the class to extend another class and separates task logic from thread management.”

Preferred: Runnable (better design).


3️⃣ Difference between Thread class and Runnable interface?
Answer:

Thread Class			Runnable Interface

Extends Thread class		Implements Runnable
Cannot extend another class	Can extend another class
Tightly coupled to threading	Better design, loose coupling
Less flexible			More flexible & preferred

Example:
In real projects, we use Runnable so the class can still extend another class while running in a thread.

